{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486979"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:52:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:52:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"223"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/223"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.13,0.02,0.09,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"223"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53966"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/223"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"223"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39437"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"5813"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"647"},{"type":"contributions","id":"725"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1663"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10715"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45713"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53966"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-month history of low back pain radiating into his buttocks and thighs. The pain is worse when standing or walking downstairs and is relieved by rest. Occasionally, he notices some numbness in his feet. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. His regular medications include metformin, sitagliptin and diltiazem. He is a non-smoker and consumes two alcoholic drinks per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. His lower limbs are warm and well perfused, with all peripheral pulses palpable. Neurological examination demonstrates a normal gait, no focal weakness in his legs, and lower limb reflexes 2+ bilaterally. Light touch sensation is intact bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following symptoms is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pain relieved by bending forward","Numbness exacerbated by foot elevation","Foot and calf pain at rest","Pain worse in the evenings","Intermittent sharp pain radiating down the back of one leg"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is consistent with spinal canal stenosis causing neurogenic claudication. Spinal canal stenosis is due to narrowing of the spinal canal causing compression of the spinal cord or nerve roots. This is most likely due to degenerative changes in older adults, and congenital and acquired defects in younger patients. Given that his pain is bilateral and in his buttocks/thighs, he likely has lumbar canal stenosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain relieved by bending forward\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely symptom to be present in this case. The pain of spinal canal stenosis tends to worsen when the back is extended (standing) and is eased by bending forwards. This is because flexion of the spine increases the diameter of the spinal canal, relieving pressure on the compressed nerves. Spinal canal stenosis usually does not require imaging, and this should only be considered in patients for surgical planning. There is no correlation between symptom severity and severity of MRI findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENumbness exacerbated by foot elevation\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with spinal stenosis. This symptom might be more indicative of peripheral arterial disease, where elevation of the foot can reduce blood flow to an already compromised limb.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFoot and calf pain at rest\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of peripheral arterial disease (PAD) in its advanced stages. While PAD can sometimes be confused with spinal stenosis due to similar claudication symptoms, the pain in PAD is typically relieved by rest, unlike in spinal stenosis where positional changes are more important.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain worse in the evenings\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical feature of spinal stenosis. Pain patterns in spinal stenosis are more related to position and activity rather than time of day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntermittent sharp pain radiating down the back of one leg\u003C/strong\u003E is indicative of sciatica, which is typically caused by a bulging disc that compresses on spinal nerve. The term \u0027sciatica\u0027 is used to describe leg pain that is localised in the distribution of one or more of the lumbosacral nerve roots (L4-S2). This pathology is unilateral as opposed to the bilateral buttocks/thigh pain experienced by this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that peripheral arterial disease (PAD) can result in claudication due to poor perfusion to the lower limbs, which can be mistaken for spinal canal stenosis. However, in PAD, the pain is typically exacerbated by exertion and relieved by rest, regardless of position. Other factors that worsen PAD include foot elevation and exertion particularly at the end of the day and at night. Other presentations of PAD include pallor, pulselessness, and poikilothermia. Progression to acute limb ischaemia can result in paraesthesia and paralysis distal to the vascular narrowing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pain of spinal canal stenosis classically worsens when the back is extended (standing) and is eased by bending forwards.","Lumbar spinal stenosis and peripheral arterial disease can present similarly, but have distinct characteristics in their symptom patterns."],"references":["Bardin LD, King P, Maher CG. Diagnostic triage for low back pain: a practical approach for primary care. Med J Aust. 2017;206(6):268-73. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28359011/","Han MH, Lee DH, Park KS, Lee YS, Kim KT, Sung JK, et al. Risk factors and incidence for peripheral arterial disease in patients with typical lumbar spinal stenosis. Korean J Spine. 2014 Sep;11(3):183-7. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4206957/","Zemaitis MR, Boll JM, Dreyer MA. Peripheral Arterial Disease. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2023 May 23. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430745/#"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39437"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"223"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39437"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-28T12:08:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-30T20:01:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"223"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53966"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":n